With my experience as a user, only get a gaming laptop if you already have a gaming pc at home and you need a gaming laptop if you are playing heavy games for an hour or 2 max. Also be prepared to get it repasted with the best most expensive paste by a professional every 4 to 6 months. I had an Alienware PC custom built for about & 7000 for a few years, then when i was upgrading, i decided to get an Asus Zephyrus top of the line at the time for $4300. The PC was a GTX i7 16 GB, and the Laptop was an RTX 3060ti i7 32 gb, i mainly played Destiny 2, Forza and Microsoft Flight Sim and boy it would get super hot. After about 5 months, as soon as I would launch any games for about 15 mins the fan would start, i had no idea that the paste inside was already rock solid.. It went like that for about 1 year, i thought there was something wrong with windows updates or malware or something.. Refreshed the laptop, then reinstalled everything fresh, was still getting loud noise and frames drop in games.. And boom one day it died.. Then i brought it to a technician and when they opened it everything was fried.. Because apparently my paste was rock solid.. The guy tood me that with gaming laptop i needed to bring it every 4 to 6 months if I wanted to keep it for a few years..

Just wanted to note this laptop isn’t heavy for a gaming laptop. I just checked the weight for the current 16” MacBook Pro and according to Apple, it weighs 4.8 pounds. It weighs 5.3 pounds for the GeForce 3050 Ti and 3060 and 6 pounds for the higher GPUs. Even with higher GPU it only weighs 1.2 pounds heavier than the much thinner MacBook Pro.  Also I wouldn’t get the i9 version. It’s the same exact cpu as i7 just with 500MHz more speed which is not worth the cost difference. The Mobile GeForce 3070 TI is the same GPU as the Mobile GeForce 3080Ti just with higher clock speed and double the video memory. Just note that Double the video ram doesn’t improve graphics all that much. Many people confuse the performance gains of increased System RAM and Video RAM.  This is why GPUs such as the desktop GeForce 1060 3GB can well outperform a GeForce 1050 Ti with 4GB of video memory. I personally don’t think the 500 dollar difference is worth the cost for minimal real world performance boost.
